WaferLLM: Large Language Model Inference at Wafer Scale

Congjie He Yeqi Huang Pei Mu Ziming Miao Jilong Xue Lingxiao Ma Fan Yang Luo Mai
Abstract

WaferLLM introduces the first wafer-scale LLM inference system, targeting accelerators with hundreds of thousands of AI cores and massive on-chip memory bandwidth. Existing LLM inference systems, designed for shared-memory GPUs, underutilize these new architectures. WaferLLM leverages a novel PLMR model to capture wafer-scale hardware characteristics, enabling fine-grained parallelism and efficient memory usage. It introduces MeshGEMM and MeshGEMV, the first GEMM and GEMV algorithms tailored for wafer-scale accelerators. Evaluations on Cerebras WSE2 show WaferLLM achieves up to 200× higher accelerator utilization, 606× faster GEMV, and 16× better energy efficiency than NVIDIA A100 GPUs. For end-to-end LLM inference, WaferLLM delivers 10–20× speedups over SGLang and vLLM on A100 clusters (see Figure 9). These gains are expected to increase as wafer-scale hardware and software mature. WaferLLM is open-sourced at https://github.com/MeshInfra/WaferLLM.

Background

B1. LLM Inference: Memory Bandwidth Bottleneck

LLM inference consists of two phases: the prefill phase (dominated by GEMM) and the decode phase (dominated by GEMV). Both phases are highly memory bandwidth-bound, as model weights (10–1,000 GB) must be repeatedly fetched from external memory. GPUs, with limited on-chip memory (~100 MB), cannot meet the bandwidth demands for high-throughput token generation. While tensor parallelism across GPUs can increase aggregate bandwidth, communication bottlenecks and per-token latency remain major challenges. The transformer-based LLM inference pipeline is dominated by self-attention and feedforward blocks. Prefill is GEMM-heavy, while decode is GEMV-heavy, with each phase stressing memory bandwidth differently.

B2. Why Wafer-Scale Accelerators?

System-on-wafer integration enables chips up to 100× larger than standard dies, integrating millions of AI-optimized cores, tens of GBs of on-chip memory, and tens of PB/s bandwidth. This architecture offers 10–1,000× improvements in bandwidth, latency, and power efficiency over conventional GPU clusters. Wafer-scale accelerators like Cerebras WSE-2 and Tesla Dojo are already deployed in production, offering cost and performance advantages for LLM inference.

B3. Challenges of Mesh-Based Memory Architectures

Wafer-scale accelerators use a massive-scale mesh network-on-chip (NoC) to connect hundreds of thousands of cores, each with local memory. This distributed, non-uniform memory architecture introduces significant challenges for LLM inference: (1) managing model and KV cache placement, (2) efficiently parallelizing GEMM and GEMV, and (3) minimizing communication overhead. Existing GPU-optimized systems perform poorly when directly ported to this architecture. Mesh NoCs are favored for their scalability, cooling, and wiring efficiency, but require new parallelism and memory management strategies for LLM workloads.

Contributions

C1. PLMR Device Model

WaferLLM introduces the PLMR model (Parallelism, Latency, Memory, Routing) to capture the unique hardware constraints of wafer-scale accelerators: (P) massive parallel cores, (L) highly non-uniform memory access latency, (M) constrained per-core local memory, and (R) limited hardware routing resources. This model guides the design of all system components for optimal utilization.

C2. Wafer-Scale LLM Parallelism

WaferLLM proposes a PLMR-compliant parallelism policy: fine-grained partitioning for prefill (GEMM) and fine-grained replication for decode (GEMV), enabling million-core parallelism and minimizing communication. It also introduces a scalable KV-cache shift method that achieves up to 400× better scalability than GPU-based approaches (see Figure 5).

C3. MeshGEMM: Wafer-Scale GEMM

MeshGEMM is a new GEMM algorithm for wafer-scale devices, using cyclic shifting and interleaving to achieve full PLMR compliance. It is 2–3× faster than SUMMA and Cannon, the state-of-the-art distributed GEMM algorithms (see Figure 9).

C4. MeshGEMV: Wafer-Scale GEMV

MeshGEMV introduces a K-tree allreduce algorithm for scalable GEMV on wafer-scale accelerators, achieving 4–8× speedup over Cerebras’s optimized GEMV and 606× faster than A100 GPU GEMV (see Figure 10).

C5. End-to-End System Implementation and Evaluation

WaferLLM is implemented on Cerebras WSE-2 with 7,000 lines of CSL and 2,000 lines of Python. It achieves 10–20× end-to-end speedup and 2.5× energy efficiency over A100 GPU clusters running SGLang and vLLM, with performance expected to improve as wafer-scale hardware and software mature.

Method

WaferLLM is designed around the PLMR model to fully exploit wafer-scale accelerators. The system partitions LLM computation across hundreds of thousands of mesh-connected cores, using PLMR-compliant parallelism for both prefill (GEMM) and decode (GEMV) phases. MeshGEMM and MeshGEMV algorithms are developed to optimize data movement, memory usage, and communication. A novel KV-cache shift method ensures balanced core utilization. The system is implemented in CSL and Python, targeting the Cerebras WSE-2 platform.

System Architecture

WaferLLM targets a mesh-based wafer-scale accelerator, where each core has local memory and is connected via a 2D mesh NoC. The architecture partitions LLM weights and activations across cores, minimizing long-distance communication. Prefill and decode phases are mapped to maximize parallelism and memory locality. The KV-cache is managed using a shift method to avoid core utilization skew.

Algorithm Design

MeshGEMM uses cyclic shifting and interleaving to partition GEMM computation and data across the mesh, ensuring bounded local memory usage and minimizing communication latency. MeshGEMV employs a K-tree allreduce to aggregate results efficiently, respecting routing constraints. Both algorithms are designed to be fully PLMR-compliant, avoiding costly matrix transpositions and maximizing on-chip bandwidth.

Results

Performance Comparison

WaferLLM achieves 2–3× faster GEMM (MeshGEMM) than SUMMA and Cannon (see Figure 9), and 4–8× faster GEMV (MeshGEMV) than Cerebras’s optimized GEMV, with a 606× speedup over A100 GPU GEMV (see Figure 10). For end-to-end LLM inference, WaferLLM delivers 10–20× speedup and 2.5× energy efficiency over SGLang and vLLM on A100 clusters. The KV-cache shift method is up to 400× more scalable than GPU-based approaches.

Scalability Analysis

Design intuitions and scalability analysis show that WaferLLM’s parallelism and memory management strategies scale efficiently to hundreds of thousands of cores, maintaining high utilization and low communication overhead as model and hardware scale increase.

Baseline Comparison

Baselines include SGLang and vLLM on NVIDIA A100 GPU clusters, SUMMA and Cannon for GEMM, and Cerebras’s optimized GEMV implementation.

Datasets

Evaluations use LLaMA3-8B, LLaMA2-13B, CodeLLaMA-34B (partial), and QWen2-72B (partial) models.

Experimental Setup

Experiments are conducted on Cerebras WSE-2 wafer-scale accelerator, using 7,000 lines of CSL and 2,000 lines of Python for system implementation. Comparisons are made against state-of-the-art GPU and distributed systems.
